---
/**
 * series.astro — "How the series fits together" (the shared reader orientation page).
 *
 * CANONICAL SOURCE: /series/series.astro at the repo root. `scripts/sync-series.mjs`
 * copies it into each book's src/pages/series.astro (predev + prebuild), so every book
 * serves an identical /series route from one source. The per-book copy is a gitignored
 * build artifact — EDIT THIS FILE, not the copies.
 *
 * Cross-book links use absolute deploy paths (/handbook/, /agentic-coding/, /architect/,
 * /design/) — one Cloudflare Worker serves all subpaths from a shared origin, so absolute
 * links resolve from inside any book. (In standalone local dev only the current book is
 * served, so sibling links 404 locally — expected; they resolve in the assembled deploy.)
 * When the books move to subdomains (#14), switch these to <BookLink> with siblingBooks set.
 */
import Base from '@brandon_m_behring/book-scaffold-astro/layouts/Base.astro';
---
<Base
  title="How the series fits together"
  description="A reader's map to the Claude books — a depth ladder from using Claude Code today, to why agentic coding works across tools, to engineering agentic systems, plus the certification study guide."
>
  <article class="prose">
    <h1>How the series fits together</h1>
    <p>
      These books are one set, read at the depth you need. Three of them form a
      <strong>depth ladder</strong> — each rung goes deeper than the last — and a fourth runs
      alongside as the certification path. Start at the rung that matches your question. Each book
      stands on its own and points onward when you want more.
    </p>

    <h2>The depth ladder</h2>

    <h3>1. Handbook — <em>use Claude Code well, today</em></h3>
    <p>
      Day-to-day practice with Claude Code: sessions, <code>CLAUDE.md</code>, workflows, config — with
      worked examples and exercises on your own project. Lean by design: it teaches the Claude-specific
      <em>how</em> in full and points up the ladder for the deeper <em>why</em>.
      <a href="/handbook/">Read the Handbook →</a>
    </p>

    <h3>2. Agentic Coding — <em>understand why it works, across tools</em></h3>
    <p>
      The principles beneath the practice, compared across Claude Code, Gemini CLI, and Codex CLI:
      where the tools <strong>converge</strong> (settled practice) and <strong>diverge</strong> (open
      design space). Read this when you want the reasoning, not just the commands — or when you're
      choosing between tools. <a href="/agentic-coding/">Read Agentic Coding →</a>
    </p>

    <h3>3. Agentic Systems Design — <em>engineer agentic systems</em></h3>
    <p>
      The deepest rung: the discipline of designing agentic systems — environment, context, tools,
      orchestration, evaluation, operations. Reference-altitude and multi-volume. Read this when
      you're building the system, not just using the tool.
      <a href="/design/">Read Agentic Systems Design →</a>
    </p>

    <h2>Alongside the ladder</h2>

    <h3>The Claude Architect's Reference — <em>pass the certification</em></h3>
    <p>
      A self-contained study guide for Anthropic's
      <a href="https://claude.com/resources/certifications"><em>Claude Certified Architect — Foundations</em></a>
      (domains D1–D5): teach-from-scratch prose, diagnostics, worked examples, and a question bank.
      Orthogonal to the ladder — the exam path. <a href="/architect/">Read the Architect's Reference →</a>
    </p>

    <h3>Glossary — <em>the shared vocabulary</em></h3>
    <p>
      A deep-linkable term layer shared by every book: one canonical definition per term, not a
      read-through book. You'll meet it through inline term links as you read.
    </p>

    <h2>Which one should I read?</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>“I just want to get work done with Claude Code.”</strong> → Handbook.</li>
      <li><strong>“Why does this work — and how do other agent CLIs compare?”</strong> → Agentic Coding.</li>
      <li><strong>“I'm designing an agentic system.”</strong> → Agentic Systems Design.</li>
      <li><strong>“I'm sitting the CCA-F exam.”</strong> → The Architect's Reference.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
</Base>
